{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636095"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:23:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:23:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.73,0,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10253"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7176"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDermatomes are areas of skin that receive sensory innervation from specific spinal nerve roots. Understanding their distribution is essential for a neurological examination and diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the dermatome distribution pattern on the trunk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diagonal bands from posterior to anterior","Horizontal bands around the trunk","Random patches without specific pattern","Spiral bands wrapping around the trunk","Vertical bands from superior to inferior"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pattern shows \u003Cstrong\u003Ehorizontal bands around the trunk\u003C/strong\u003E. Thoracic dermatomes run horizontally around the trunk in a circumferential pattern, with minimal overlap between adjacent levels. This arrangement reflects the embryological development and segmental nature of spinal innervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom patches without specific pattern\u003C/strong\u003E - Dermatomes follow a precise and predictable pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertical bands from superior to inferior\u003C/strong\u003E - While dermatomes run vertically on the limbs, they are horizontal on the trunk\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagonal bands from posterior to anterior\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern does not exist; dermatomes maintain a horizontal orientation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpiral bands wrapping around the trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - Dermatomes do not spiral but maintain a consistent horizontal level\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey clinical landmarks for dermatomes include T4 at the nipple level, T10 at the umbilicus, and L1 at the groin. This predictable pattern helps clinicians localise neurological lesions during physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermatomes are areas of skin innervated by specific spinal nerve roots","Thoracic dermatomes run horizontally around the trunk in a circumferential pattern","Key dermatome landmarks: T4 at nipple level, T10 at umbilicus, L1 at groin"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cDermatomes radiculaires humains\u201d by CYP3A42D6 is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Dermatomes_radiculaires_humains.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21335"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21335"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VXwpxJE01M6zNpkNLwZWZOu8GBiAa9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VXwpxJE01M6zNpkNLwZWZOu8GBiAa9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":813}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T17:46:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T17:46:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/